label.value: activated CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell proliferation

value.value: The expansion of an activated CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell population by cell division.

label.value: CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell cytokine production

value.value: Any process that contributes to cytokine production by a CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: Any process that contributes to cytokine production by a T-helper 1 cell.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: Any process that contributes to cytokine production by a T-helper 2 cell.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: The appearance of granzyme A due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: The directed movement of a natural killer cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).
The region of the myelin sheath furthest from the axon.
The region of the myelin sheath nearest to the axon.

label.value: protein localization to myelin sheath abaxonal region

value.value: Any process in which a protein is transported to, and/or maintained in, the abaxonal region of the myelin sheath. The abaxonal region is the region of the myelin sheath furthest from the axon.
Any process that modulates the pH of the lysosomal lumen, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.
Any process that increases the pH of the lysosomal lumen, measured by the concentration of the hydrogen ion.
Any process involved in sustaining the fidelity and copy number of DNA trinucleotide repeats. DNA trinucleotide repeats are naturally occurring runs of three base-pairs.

The directed movement of a B cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of cardiolipin (1,3-bis(3-phosphatidyl)glycerol), releasing phosphatidic acid (PA).
A process in which a symbiont moves from one side of an epithelium to the other within its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
Binding to chemokine (C-C motif) ligand 19.
Binding to chemokine (C-C motif) ligand 21.
The binding of a mesangial cell to the extracellular matrix via adhesion molecules. A mesangial cell is a cell that encapsulates the capillaries and venules in the kidney.

The chemical reactions and pathways occurring in the cytoplasm and resulting in the breakdown of a ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule, initiated by the enzymatic addition of a sequence of adenylyl residues (polyadenylation) at the 3' end the target rRNA truncated degradation intermediate.

label.value: dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve maturation

value.value: A developmental process, independent of morphogenetic (shape) change, that is required for the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve to attain its fully functional state.

label.value: dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve morphogenesis

value.value: The process in which the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve is generated and organized. Morphogenesis pertains to the creation of form.

label.value: dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve structural organization

value.value: The process that contributes to the act of creating the structural organization of the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve. This process pertains to the physical shaping of a rudimentary structure.

label.value: dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve formation

value.value: The process that gives rise to the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve. This process pertains to the initial formation of a structure from unspecified parts.

label.value: motor neuron precursor migration involved in dorsal motor nucleus of vagus nerve formation

value.value: The orderly movement of a motor neuron precursor cell that contributes to formation of the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus nerve.

label.value: cell chemotaxis to fibroblast growth factor

value.value: The directed movement of a motile cell in response to the presence of fibroblast growth factor (FGF).

The directed movement of an endothelial cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis).

label.value: endothelial cell chemotaxis to fibroblast growth factor

value.value: The directed movement of an endothelial cell in response to the presence of fibroblast growth factor (FGF).

label.value: B cell chemotaxis across high endothelial venule

value.value: The movement of a B cell to cross a high endothelial venule in response to an external stimulus.

A non-membranous macromolecular complex containing proteins and translationally silenced mRNAs. RNA granules contain proteins that control the localization, stability, and translation of their RNA cargo. Different types of RNA granules (RGs) exist, depending on the cell type and cellular conditions.

The series of molecular signals initiated by interleukin-4 binding to its receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

The series of molecular signals initiated by interleukin-13 binding to its receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus

value.value: The regulated release of proinsulin from secretory granules (B granules) in the B cells of the pancreas; accompanied by cleavage of proinsulin to form mature insulin, in response to a glucose stimulus.

label.value: positive regulation of insulin secretion involved in cellular response to glucose stimulus

value.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of insulin that contributes to the response of a cell to glucose.

The process in which the anatomical structures of the pronephric glomerulus are generated and organized. The pronephric glomerulus is part of the pronephric nephron and is restricted to one body segment.

definition.value: This term is intended for annotation of fish and other organisms which contain a glomerulus as part of the pronephric nephron. It should not be used for annotation of Xenopus, which contains a pronephric glomus rather than a glomerulus.

value.value: The progression of the pronephric proximal tubule over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A pronephric nephron tubule is an epithelial tube that is part of the pronephros.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the pronephric distal tubule over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A pronephric nephron tubule is an epithelial tube that is part of the pronephros.

label.value: pronephric nephron tubule epithelial cell differentiation

value.value: The process in which relatively unspecialized cells acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize the cells of the pronephric nephron tubule as it progresses from its formation to the mature state.

The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires the specialized structural and/or functional features of an angioblast cell. Angioblasts are one of the two products formed from hemangioblast cells (the other being pluripotent hemopoietic stem cells).

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of CD80, a CD marker that occurs on antigen presenting cells such as activated B cells and monocytes that provides a co-stimulatory signal necessary for T cell activation and survival.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of CD86, a CD marker that occurs on antigen presenting cells that provides co-stimulatory signals necessary for T cell activation and survival.

The directed movement of a mature natural killer cell guided by a specific chemical concentration gradient. Movement may be towards a higher concentration (positive chemotaxis) or towards a lower concentration (negative chemotaxis). A mature natural killer cell is a natural killer cell that is developmentally mature and expresses a variety of inhibitory and activating receptors that recognize MHC class and other stress related molecules.

The process of providing, via surface-bound receptor-ligand pairs, a second, antigen-independent, signal in addition to that provided by the T cell receptor to augment CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell activation.
A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of nickel ions within a cell.

label.value: cell migration involved in kidney development

value.value: The orderly movement of a cell from one site to another that will contribute to the progression of the kidney over time, from its formation to the mature organ.

label.value: cell migration involved in metanephros development

value.value: The orderly movement of a cell from one site to another that will contribute to the progression of the metanephric kidney over time, from its formation to the mature organ.

The orderly movement of undifferentiated metanephric mesenchymal cells (precursors to metanephric mesangial cells) from the mesenchyme into the cleft of the developing glomerulus, during development of the metanephros.

label.value: platelet-derived growth factor receptor-alpha signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated a ligand binding to an alpha-type platelet-derived growth factor receptor (PDGFalpha) on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: platelet-derived growth factor receptor-beta signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a ligand to a beta-type platelet-derived growth factor receptor (PDGFbeta) on the surface of a signal-receiving cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

A postsynaptic membrane that is part of a host cell. A postsynaptic membrane is a specialized area of membrane facing the presynaptic membrane on the tip of the nerve ending and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft). Neurotransmitters transmit the signal across the synaptic cleft to the postsynaptic membrane.

label.value: positive regulation of metanephric mesenchymal cell migration by platelet-derived growth factor receptor-beta signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of metanephric mesenchymal cell migration resulting from the platelet-derived growth factor receptor-beta signaling pathway.
